# Git Cheat Sheet

A personal reference covering setup, daily workflow, and troubleshooting for working with Git on macOS.

---

## 1. Initial macOS Setup

```bash
# Install Homebrew (if not already installed)
/bin/bash -c "$(curl -fsSL https://raw.githubusercontent.com/Homebrew/install/HEAD/install.sh)"

# Install Git
brew install git
git --version
```

### Git Identity & Config

```bash
git config --global user.name "Your Name"
git config --global user.email "you@example.com"
git config --global color.ui auto

# View all settings
git config --global --list
```

---

## 2. SSH Key Setup

```bash
# Generate an Ed25519 key (preferred over RSA)
ssh-keygen -t ed25519 -C "youremail@example.com" -f ~/.ssh

# Start agent and add key
eval "$(ssh-agent -s)"
ssh-add --apple-use-keychain ~/.ssh

# Copy public key to clipboard, then add it on GitHub
# Settings → SSH and GPG Keys → New SSH key
pbcopy < ~/.ssh/id_ed25519.pub

# Test connection
ssh -T git@github.com
```

### `~/.ssh/config`

```
Host *
  IdentityFile ~/.ssh/id_ed25519
  IdentitiesOnly yes
  AddKeysToAgent yes
  UseKeychain yes
```

`IdentitiesOnly yes` forces SSH to use only the specified key — fixes the issue where it defaults to an old `id_rsa` and asks for a forgotten passphrase.

