## 5. Daily Workflow

```bash
git checkout main		# switch to main branch
git pull origin main		# update the local main branch to match the remote main's branch
git branch              	# list local branches
git checkout branch_name	# switch to the branch you want to work on. 
git rebase main  		# Update the said branch so it sits on top of updated main

# make changes			# Performed task(s)
git restore <file>		# Discard changes in working directory.
git status                  	# see what's changed
git add .                   	# stage all changes or 
git add file_name             	# stage only one file
git commit -m "add message"	#commit changes
git push origin current-branch-name

# Go online to Github
# Compare and create a Pull Request → review → merge on main branch, optionally delete the said branch then return to the terminal:

git checkout main		# switch to main branch
git pull origin main		# update the local main branch to match the remote main's branch
git checkout branch_name	# switch btw branches to update it against the local main branch 
git rebase main  		# Update the said branch so it sits on top of updated main 

```
## Quick Fix

```bash
git restore --staged .		# un-stage only one file or directory
git restore --staged filename	# unstage all files and directories
git reset [file]      # unstage a file while retaining the changes in working directory

```

> **Important:** pulling `main` does **not** update other branches automatically. Each branch must be updated on its own — run the last two commands for each branch in local repo. Also see below for additional info.

