## 6. Fetch vs Pull vs Rebase

| | `git fetch` | `git pull` | `git pull --rebase` |
|---|---|---|---|
| Downloads remote changes | ✅ | ✅ | ✅ |
| Merges into current branch | ❌ | ✅ | ✅ |
| Creates a merge commit | ❌ | Often ✅ | ❌ |
| Keeps history linear | ✅ | ❌ | ✅ |

```bash
# Fetch — see what changed without touching your work
git fetch origin
git log origin/main --oneline
git diff HEAD origin/main

# Rebase — replay your branch on top of latest main
git checkout feature/initial-structure
git fetch origin
git rebase origin/main

# Interactive rebase — clean up commits before a PR
git rebase -i HEAD~3
# pick / squash / reword / drop

# Push after rebase (safer than --force)
git push --force-with-lease origin feature/initial-structure
```

**Golden rule:** never rebase a branch others are also working on — it rewrites commit history.

