## 9. Create a Local-Only / Network-Shared Repos (No GitHub)

### local-Only, no sharing
```bash
git init my-project
cd my-project
git add .
git commit -m "first commit"
# No remote repo, therefore no push/pull
```

### Bare repo — share over your local network via SSH or Users on same system. 

```bash
# On the host machine
mkdir -p ~/git-server		# -p flag means: Create parent directories as needed, and don't complain if they already exist.
cd ~/git-server
git init --bare cybersec-homelab.git

# Connect your working repo to it
cd ~/Projects/cybersec-homelab
git remote add origin ~/git-server/cybersec-homelab.git
git push -u origin main

# Find your Mac's local IP for others to clone
ipconfig getifaddr en0

# Someone else on the network clones via:
git clone user@192.168.1.x:~/git-server/cybersec-homelab.git
```

| Step | GitHub hosted | Local bare repo |
|---|---|---|
| Clone | `git clone git@github.com:...` | `git clone user@192.168.1.x:~/git-server/repo.git` |
| Pull request | GitHub UI | None — push directly or merge locally |
| Access control | GitHub permissions | SSH user accounts / `authorized_keys` |

Restrict a user to git-only access (no full shell):
```bash
chsh -s $(which git-shell) username
```

